    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-11-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-11-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="2"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Adams</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 414]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-11-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 30, 1862.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have received your despatch of the 13th of
                    November, (No. 259,) and also your despatch of November 15, (No. 261.) They
                    relate to the proposition recently made by the Emperor of France to the Emperor
                    of Russia and to the Queen of Great Britain, to join him in recommending an
                    armistice in our unhappy civil war. Your statements upon that subject are very
                    interesting and satisfactory. At the same time I do not propose to discuss the
                    transaction.</p>
                <p>You will learn the impression which it has made upon the President from the copy
                    which I send you of my despatch of this date to Mr. Dayton. I send a. copy of
                    the same paper to Mr. Taylor, in Russia; and thus, by the President’s direction,
                    I leave the French proposal to take its place among the incidents already past
                    of the lamentable civil war of which we again think we are beginning to see an
                    approaching end.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic"
                            >&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>(The enclosure will be found in the correspondence with France.)</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
